{
  "ADUs": {
    "ADU1": {
      "text": "The early modern influence of Epicureanism was both enormous and diffuse.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU2": {
      "text": "Many early moderns used the term 'Epicurean' to describe other people's views, but they almost never described their own views that way.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU3": {
      "text": "Moreover, many different sorts of view were called Epicurean.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU4": {
      "text": "Understanding how they used this category helps us understand early modern philosophical debates.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU5": {
      "text": "We do not aim at an exhaustive survey of early modern Epicureanism, which would be impossible.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU6": {
      "text": "Instead, we look at a few interesting and important episodes in the life of early modern Epicureanism, focusing on Epicureanism in natural philosophy.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU7": {
      "text": "Gassendi's project of constructing a positive representation of Epicurus has a number of aspects.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU8": {
      "text": "Above all, he wants to represent Epicureanism as a serious philosophical system, like Aristotelianism and Stoicism—and ultimately to show that Epicureanism was preferable to either, both in terms of explanatory power and theological acceptability.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU9": {
      "text": "Gassendi tries to figure out how Epicurus's reputation for immorality had developed in the first place.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU10": {
      "text": "He concludes that it was due to 'the hatred and calumny of Zeno, Cleanthes, Chrysippus and other Stoics.'",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU11": {
      "text": "Gassendi also argues that Epicureanism is ultimately easier to reconcile with the doctrines of the Catholic Church than Aristotelianism.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU12": {
      "text": "Cudworth insists that Epicureanism is atheistic.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU13": {
      "text": "Cudworth says that Epicurus made 'Sensless Atoms to be the first Principles, not only of all Bodies (for that was a thing admitted before by Empedocles and other Atomists that were Theists) but also of All things whatsoever in the whole Universe.'",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU14": {
      "text": "Cudworth argues instead that Epicurus went too far in using atomism to explain everything in the world.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU15": {
      "text": "Cudworth insists that Epicurus's claim to believe in gods is insincere.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU16": {
      "text": "Epicurus, that is, held views that implied atheism, and knew it, but said he believed in some gods in order to avoid criticism.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU17": {
      "text": "Cudworth and Gassendi, then, identify similar central themes of Epicureanism, including atomism, materialism about the human mind, and a deflationary approach to religion, if not outright atheism.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU18": {
      "text": "These views do not entail each other, yet they fit together well as a group.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU19": {
      "text": "If you think that the content of the natural world is exhausted by atoms moving in the void, then you will plausibly also adopt the other views.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU20": {
      "text": "As this list of 'Epicurean' doctrines and figures shows, the category 'Epicurean' is both vague and elastic.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU21": {
      "text": "Nevertheless, it is useful for two related, reasons.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU22": {
      "text": "One is that the category played an important role in seventeenth- and eighteenth-century discussions.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU23": {
      "text": "Another reason has to do with today's scholarly landscape.",
      "label": "premise"
    }
  },
